Confirm that no errors appear and the theme loads with a basic structure.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 3. Create template and template part folders\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 With the theme activated, set up folders that define your site\'92s layout and reusable sections.\cb1 \
\cb3 Inside your theme folder, create two new folders: 
\f3\i templates
\f1\i0  and 
\f3\i parts
\f1\i0 . These will hold 
\f3\i .html
\f1\i0  files used by the Site Editor.\cb1 \
\cb3 Files in 
\f3\i templates/
\f1\i0  define full-page layouts (e.g., 
\f3\i index.html, page.html
\f1\i0 ), while files in 
\f3\i parts/
\f1\i0  define reusable blocks like headers and footers (e.g., 
\f3\i header.html, footer.html
\f1\i0 ).\cb1 \
\cb3 Keep the structure flat \'96 WordPress scans both folders automatically.\cb1 \
\cb3 Don\'92t include PHP files; block themes are rendered entirely in HTML and block markup.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 4. Build theme templates\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Now you\'92ll define how different parts of the site are rendered using blocks and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-block-templates/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul block templates}}.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Create a file named 
\f3\i index.html
\f1\i0  inside the 
\f3\i templates/
\f1\i0  folder and add basic layout markup:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 <!-- wp:template-part \{"slug":"header"\} /-->\
<!-- wp:post-title /-->\
<!-- wp:post-content /-->\
<!-- wp:template-part \{"slug":"footer"\} /-->
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
In 
\f3\i parts/
\f1\i0 , create 
\f3\i header.html
\f1\i0  with markup like:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 <!-- wp:group -->\
  <!-- wp:site-title /-->\
  <!-- wp:navigation /-->\
<!-- /wp:group -->
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0
\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Create 
\f3\i footer.html
\f1\i0  in the same way (e.g., a group with site info or footer menu).\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Add more templates in 
\f3\i templates/
\f1\i0 , like 
\f3\i single.html, page.html
\f1\i0 , and 
\f3\i 404.html
\f1\i0 , depending on your site\'92s needs.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Use the Site Editor to visually design and export templates if you prefer not to write them manually.\cb1 \
\cb3 For a more modular approach, consider {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-block-development/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul creating custom blocks}} using {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/resources/blocks/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul ACF Blocks}}, which come as part of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/pro/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul ACF PRO}}. They integrate directly with block themes and offer full control over markup and fields. This includes the ability to display custom field values without any complex state management or REST endpoints.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
